A drum containing hazardous waste from a permanent household hazardous waste site was unloaded from a box truck and placed on the dock at the truck transfer facility.  The drum was later moved to another location on the dock, when a small amount of leakage was  noticed on the floor.  Facility personel donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and overpacked the drum into a suitable salvage container.  The spilled material was cleaned up and the cleanup material was also placed into the salvage drum.  The shipment was then loaded into a trailer destined for the intended waste disposal facility.
column169: At the time the container was accepted for transportaiton, no evidence of damage or leaking was observed.  It is suspected that a small pinhole leak developed allowing approximatley 2 ounces of material to escape from the package.  In order to prevnt a recurrence, both the individuals responsible for preparing the container for transportaiton and the driver accepting the container have been re-instructed to conduct a thorough container inspection and take appropriate actions should a container be identified with suspect structural integrity.

column168: A van trailer containing multiple shipments of hazardous waste was being unloaded at Clean Harbor's in transit storage facility for the purpose of consolidating less than truckload shipments into another trailer destined for the intended waste disposal facility.  In the process of unloading, it was noticed that one 5 gallon container was not completely upright and leaking.  The crew donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and cleaned the leak with an absorbent pad.  The closure device was resealed according to the container closure instructions.  The shipment was then loaded onto the trailer destined for the intended waste disposal facility.  The absorbent pad was containerized and placed into storage pending off-site disposal.
column169: The individuals responsible for preparing the container for transportatin were notfieid of the incident and were advised to insure that proper container closure instructions are followed.  Additionally, the persons loading the trailer were retrained in proper blocking and bracing of all items loaded in trailers.

column168: LTCX 1610 (DOT 113A90W tank car) was reported venting in the railyard and it was cordoned off awaiting inspection. A BNSF Mechanical/Hazardous Material responder inspected LTCX 1610 and reported that the vent source was from a closed valve within the side equipment control cabinet. The shipper/consignee was contacted and sent a technician responder to end the vapor release. The technician bled down the internal pressure that had built-up within LTCX 1610 which essentially ended the vapor vent. The closed main fill valve was reported as the leak source and appeared to be leaking at the valve stem area. This fill valve possibly was over tightened resulting in damage to the valve stem packing material. The packing was adjusted with additional packing applied. This valve was earmarked for replacement by the shipper technician. After monitoring, no further vapor vent was evident. Response was concluded by approximately 1500 hrs. CST, 11/02/09.

On 11/3/09 at 08:32 hours, car department personnel in the CSXT Selkirk Yard discovered PROX43077, a loaded tank car of Styrene Monomer, stabilized, leaking from around the bottom outlet valve area. The car was isolated and the shipper, Ineos Nova LTD, (Representative Chuck McCandess - 281-474-1027) was notified via CHEMTREC (Report #2009-11-03-00047). NYSDEC was contacted (Report 0908703).  Paul Watson, a CSXT Environmental Manager and Sentinel Plus, was dispatched to the scene and found product dripping from the bottom outlet valve operating shaft packing nut. The packing nut was tightened and the leak stopped.  The car was staged for three hours with no evidence of product leakage then released for transport.    An AAR QA Program, 7.1 Nonconformance Report was completed for this incident.  Note: This incident did not require a special shipping move.  Cause Code: 547  NARRI:  2 (5+1+0) x (2+0) = 24

column168: On 11/18/09 at 01:25 hrs., personnel in the CSX Transportation Demmler yard, in McKeesport , PA, reported an odor of Ammonia, Anhydrous, coming from residue tank car CWBX 300034. The car was isolated and the shipper, United States Steel Corporation, Clairton, PA was notified via CHEMTREC (Report #2009111800006). United States Steel Corporation representative, Stacey Sneberger, authorized CSX Transportation to dispatch a CSXT emergency response contractor, Specialized Professional Services, Inc. (SPSI), to the scene. Jack Bailie, SPSI representative, inspected the pressure relief valve and noted a slight vapor leak at the valve seat.  SPS personneI replaced the "O" rings and retaining cap for the pressure relief device and the leak stopped. CSX Transportation placed the tank car on hold pending a "leak test" by SPSI in accordance with U. S. DOT Regulations or the shipper obtaining FRA Movement Approval to forward the car.  Cause Code:  414  NARRI: 5 (4+9+0) X (2+0) = 130

column168: This order was 60 containers stacked on 2 pallets side by side in a trailer. When the first pallet was pulled out, it caused the containers on the adjacent pallet to shift foward. The forklift operator then proceeded to use the pallet he had pulled out on the left to push the pallet on the right, attempted to realign the shifted containers. He used the corner of the pallet on his lift to push the containers on the right pallet, and this caused the puncture of one of the containers on the pallet on the right. The size of the puncture was an estimated 3 inches.
column169: This was just a poor decision made by a relatively new employee. More caution should have been taken in pulling out the first pallet, and after the containers on the right pallet had shifted, the forklift operator needed to re-stack the pallet rather than try to align it with force. This employee will be re-trained on the proper handling of hazardous materials and be re-certified on the forklift.

A box truck was being loaded with hazardous waste shipments at the generator's dock.  Employees, who were wearing the appropriate personal protective equipment, were moving drums from the storage area onto the truck with a drum dolly.  The noticed that a drum was leaking when they began moving it.  They flipped the drum upside down to stop the leak and noticed a small pinhole leak from a corroded area of the bottom of the drum.  The drum was then placed into a suitable salvage drum along with material used to clean up the spill.  The shipment was then loaded onto the box truck for further shipment to the intended waste disposal facility.  Incident was reported to Tennessee Emergency Management Authority and assigned incident # 1968.
column169: During the loading operation, the shipper and driver identified the leaking container.  It was discovered that the visible portion of the non bulk package showed no sign of damage or leaking but when it was moved, corrosion was observed on the bottom of the container.  In order to rprevent a recurrence, the shipper has been advised to ensure that containers are peridoically inspected and any that show sign of deterioration or aging should be repackaed to preclude an unintentional release.

CHECK THE FLOORS OF TRAILER TO ENSURE NO SHARP OBJECTS, NAILS, PIECES OF WOOD, DAMAGED PALLETS ARE PROTRUDING THAT COULD CAUSE EASY DAMAGED TO DRUMS, PAILS, BAGS TOTES AND OTHER PACKAGINGS. column169: RETRAINING ON SAFE USE AND OPERATION OF THE FORKLIFT. CHECK BRAKES FOR PROPER AND SAFE USE. IF ATTACHMENTS USED FOR FORKLIFT ARE IMPROPERLY WORKING, THEY MUST BE REMOVED FROM SERVICE AND BE REPAIRED OR TAKEN OUT OF SERVICE PERMANENTLY. MAINTENANCE MUST BE DONE PROPERLY TO ENSURE SAFETY USB FOR ALL. FREIGHT PLACED ON DOCK MUST BE SECURED AND PROPERLY BLOCKED AND SHROUDED TO AVOID EASY PUNCTURING FROM OTHER FREIGHT OR FORKLIFT. DISCUSS DURING PRESHIFT ON THE SAFETY OF DOCKING, REMOVING AND TRANSFERRING CHEMICAL, LIQUID AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS. BEING AWARE OF SURROUNDINGS WHEN WORKING. ON THE DOCK AND WHILE TRANSFERRING PACKAGES OF CHEMICALS, LIQUIDS OR HAZARDOUS MATERIALS! PAILS OF LIQUIDS, CHEMICALS AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS MUST BE COMPLETELY SHROUDED USING DUNNAGE, MTY PALLETS AND PLYWOOD TO PREVENT EASY DAMAGED AND PUNCTURING. LEAVE PAIL OF HAZARDOUS OR CHEMICAL IN THE BAY UNTIL TRAILER IS READY FOR CLOSE. EMPLOYEE GIVEN COACHING ON LOADING AND DOCK AWARENESS.

column169: CHECK THE WALL OF THE TRAILER. INSPECT AREAS THOROUGHLY TO ENSURE UNSAFE CONDITIONS ARE NOT PRESENT TO AVOID EASY DAMAGING TO PACKAGES OF DRUMS, PAILS, TOTES, BAGS AND OTHER PACKAGING CONTAINING HAZARDOUS MATERIALS OR CHEMICALS. CHECK THE FLOORS OF TRAILER TO ENSURE NO SHARP OBJECTS, NAILS, PIECES OF WOOD, DAMAGE PALLETS ARE PROTRUDING THAT COULD CAUSE EASY DAMAGED TO DRUMS, PAILS, BAGS TOTES AND OTHER PACK AGINGS. PAILS, BAGS, TOTES AND DRUMS OF LIQUIDS, CHEMICAL AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS MUST BE PROPERLY BLOCKED AND BRACED TO PREVENT FROM BEING DAMAGED BY ADJACENT FREIGHT OR SHARP AND POINTED OBJECTS, SUCH AS A NAIL. USE DUNNAGE,PLYWOOD, MTY PALLETS AND OR AIRBAGS TO PROPERLY SHROUD, BLOCK, BRACE AND SECURE FREIGHT AND THE ENTIRE LOAD.RETRAINING IN PROPER AND SAFE LOADING OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS AND CHEMICAL FREIGHT, USING PROPER AND SAFE BLOCKING AND BRACING LOADING TECHNIQUES.

column168: While prepareing to unload Rolloff box at the intended waste management facility,  the axle on the rolloff trailer failed allowing the roll-off container to tilt to one side. Facility personnel along withthe vehicle operator immediately placed a containment pbucket under the leak alon with absorbent pads.  The facility's maintenance crew was dispatched and proceeded to jack the box up to a level position.  Once level, a replacement vehicle removed the container and delivered the box to the receiving cell where the material was processed for disposal.  The material collected from the release was placed in the container and disposed of as well.      The damaged tralier was placed out os service pending repairs and the roll-off box was inspected to insure that all closure devices were in palce and operational.

column168: TRUCK LOADED PROPANE AT THE CONOCO PHILLIPS PIPELINE @ APP. 5:30AM.  AFTER LEAVING THE PIPELINE, TRUCK TRAVELLED ABOUT 5 MILES WEST ON HIGHWAY 50 ENROUTE TO HIS DESTINATION.  THE DRIVER FELT HIS FRONT TIRE DROP OFF THE PAVEMENT AND THE SOFTER SOIL CAUSED THE TRUCK TO BE PULLED TO THE RIGHT AND INTO THE BARROW DITCH WHERE IT OVERTURNED.  ALTHOUGH THERE WAS NO LEAKAGE OF PRODUCT, DUE TO THE POTENTIAL DANGER TRAFFIC WAS REROUTED TO FRONTAGE ROADS OF HWY 50  THE ENTIRE HWY & FRONTAGE ROADS WERE INITIALLY CLOSED FOR LESS THAN 1 HOUR AFTER WHICH THE FRONTAGE ROADS RE-OPENED.
column169: WE BELIEVE THE WRECK WAS CAUSED BY DRIVERS LACK OF ATTENTION TO THE TRUCKS POSITION WITHIN THE LANES OF THE HIGHWAY.  THE SHOULDER OF THE HIGHWAY WAS SOFTER THAN USUAL DUE TO WET WEATHER IN THE DAYS PROCEEDING THE WRECK.

Timeline Incident 11/10/09 GS Robins 126 Chouteau St.Louis, Mo    11/9/09 Gary Durbin dispatch driver (Mark Hiestand) to pickup trailer 7001 from Tank Trailer Cleaning and load at Slay Terminal. We do not have our own cleaning rack in Granite City, IL. Gary Durbin used the clean trailer list we get every morning from Tank Trailer Cleaning in E.St.Louis,IL . He selected trailer 7001 from the list.  Trailer 7001 is a Brenner DOT407 Stainless Steel tank trailer. Tank Trailer cleaning had omitted the ALU part of the trailer number on the list they sent to him that morning. Coal City Cob only owns 2 aluminum trailers out of 355 trailers. We have now changed the unit number on the one aluminum trailer we have left in our fleet.    11/10/09  0700 Driver(Mark Hiestand) pickup trailer ALU7001 1971 Fruehauf MC307 Vin#OMN558003 IL Lic# T44237 at Tank Trailer Cleaning in East St.Louis, IL  0800 Driver arrived at Slay Terminal at the Foot of Barton St St.Louis, Mo to load Aprox 2000 gallons of 50% Sodium Hydroxide. After loading he proceeds to GS Robins at 126 Chouteau St.Louis, Mo to load approx 2000 gallons of water, to make 25% Sodium Hydroxide.  0830 After loading and receiving paperwork driver noticed a leak while parked in the parking lot of GS Robins.  0830 Driver called his Terminal Manager Gary Durbin at 5529 Dial Drive Suite#7 in Granite City, IL at 618-797-5471.  0835 Gary called Safety Director Russell Landry in Waxahachie, TX. He called XL Environmental (Mike Dowger at 800-823-7351)for assistance at the scene. I then called Mr Buscher  at 314-259-5108 at GS Robins. I called Steve Finn at ADM the Customer requesting Coal City Cob to pickup this product at 517-451-4850.  0840 Gary Dispatched a driver and trl# 70144 2005 Bulk DOT407 stainless steel trailer to the GS Robins.  0900 Second trailer arrives and connected to ALU7001. Product then unloaded into trailer#70144.  0900 GS Robins called ER Crew to clean up leaking product, dug up the contaminated soil, and replaced.  Xl Environmental contacted the ER Company at the scene.    Weighed loaded trailer and by the weights we lost 250 gallons of the product on the ground.  70144 loaded on our yard in Granite City, IL waiting on Buyer.    Mike Dowger  at XL Environemental (Greenwich Ins) handled all state reporting and reports for Coal City Cob Company Inc.    ALU7001 was washed down and sent to Tank Trailer Cleaning for cleaning and inspection. The trailer is a total lose and will be scrapped out shortly.

On 11/06/09 at 11:00 hrs., personnel in the CSXT Boyles Yard in Birmingham AL, discovered NATX78184, a residue tank car of Flammable Liquids N.O.S., leaking from the bottom outlet. The car was isolated in the car shop and the shipper was notified via CHEMTREC (Report #2009-11-06-00094).  CSXT Sentinels, Keith Sapp and Brett Treywick, were dispatched to the scene and found the bottom outlet cap was less than tool tight. The bottom outlet cap was tightened tool tight and the leak stopped.  The car was released for transport. This incident did not require a special switching move. This information was relayed to the shipper contact person Chris Bond, 205 907 8007, Pegasus National       No 7.1 Nonconformance report is required.   Cause Code: 149  NARRI:   5 (4+1+0) x (2+0) = 50

This railcar was observed leaking during switching operations.  The railcar was isolated.  Upon closer inspection, one of the manway bolt washers was between the manway cover and the tank nozzle flange causing it not to get a good seal.  The manway was resecured and the leak was stopped.  No injuries.

A BNSF outbound train consist inspection in the railyard revealed DBUX 300059 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) dripping residue product from its bottom outlet cap (BOC). DBUX 300059 was carefully setout of the train and isolated in the railyard. BNSF and contract hazardous material responders inspected DBUX 300059 and reported finding the bottom operated bottom outlet valve (BOV) in its closed position with its operating handle pinned. The BOC was tool tight. The BOC was carefully removed for gasket inspection. Inside the BOC, two BOC gaskets were found, with one of these deteriorated; and a build-up of fuel oil sludge. The BOC was cleaned, along with the remaining serviceable gasket. Teflon tape was applied to the BOC threads. The BOC was reapplied and properly tool tightened. Afterwards, no further residue product drips were observed during the monitoring period. The BOV was tagged for inspection/repair since product appeared to be by-passing the closed valve. DBUX 300059 was directed to a repair facility. The residue product that impacted the ground which appeared to be accompanied with water was treated with a bio-treatment agent. DBUX 300059 has been top loaded/unloaded in its previous transport cycles, and any water or moisture inside the tank migrated to the tank bottom. Response was concluded by 1330 hrs. CDT, 11/06/09.

column168: A van trailer containing hazardous waste was en route to the intended waste management facility.  During the course of the trip, the load was staged at a CLean Harbors 10 day in transit storage location pending continued transportation.  A subsequent driver was dispathed to continue the transportation and during his pre-trip load inspeciton, identified a small amount of material leaking from the trailer.  Facility management was notified and a response crew was assembled to investigate the source of the leak.  Using appropriate personnel protective equipment, the crew entered the trailer and determined that a cubic yard container of paint was leaking. Further investigation indicated that an individual paint can packaged within the container had a loose lid that allowed paint to escape from the package.  The crew secured the container and repackaged the inner container involved along with all contaminated absorbent material. In addition, they secured the original package and sent it, along withthe clean-up debris to the intended waste management facility.
column169: The material involved in the incident were paints collected at a waste collection event designed for home owners to discard household hazardous wastes.  The individuals involved in the packaging of this material were cautioned to inspect each container and insure all closures are in place to precelude this type of incident.

column168: Freight was slagged on dock ready for loading on delivery route when DSR, noticed that the side of the skid that the jugs were loaded on was wet. He notified myself to report a possible spill. I had  him go get rubber gloves, salvage drum and paper towel as at first glance looked as if the cap on the jugs were not tightened fully. Upon further investigation the caps were sealed and the one jug that was wet on top's cap was tightened fully as well. I lifted the jug and it appeared to be half empty with no sign of damage to the jug itself. I went back to the trailer from which it was unloaded, 313-6086 and, didn't see any sign of leaking in the trailer. Going back to the skid I carefully looked at the skid to determine if it had been leaking for a long time or not. The skid was indeed wet but not saturated. I placed the half empty jug in a five gallon salvage drum sealed the drum and sent the rest of the freight out for delivery. I contacted Safety and told him the situation. The customer, Quaker Chemical refused the entire order do to the palette being wet and some residue on on lid on the bottom of skid. Freight was brought back to terminal and placed into Haz-mat Bay.

After removing the pallet from the trailer and looking closely you could see where someone had hit the case with the forklift blades between the pallet and the bottom case, damaging two cans. column168: A vehicle containing hazardous waste was en route from the shipper's location to the intended waste management facility.  During the course of the trip, the driver made a routine stop at Clean Harbor's in transit storage facility located in Bridgeport, NJ. The purpose of this stop was to consolidate less than truckload quantities for continued transportation.  While n storage, facility personnel idenfied 3 containers that had a small amount of material leaking from the top closure. Using appropriate personnel protctive equipment, facility personnel entered the trailer and identified 3 containers that had cracked gaskets.  The 3 containers were plced into suitable salvage drums along with all materials used to absorbe the estimated 1 gallon of liquid that escaped onto the floor of the van trailer as well as the material used to decontminate the sides of the containers and the trailer floor.  Once secured, the load was released and was sent to the intended waste management facility.
column169: At the time the containers were accepted for transportation, no evidence of leaking was observed. It is believed that the drum gaskets were defective being that no  contact marks were notice at the leak area. The shipper was notified of the incident and has been advised to ensure that all future shipments were inspected to insure the closure devices were in good working order.

column25: SG SOLUTIONS A/O INTERNATIONAL COMMODITIES EXPORT CORP.
column168: On 11/24/2009 at 02:05 hrs., personnel in the CSXT Avon Yard in Avon, IN reported a strong sulfur odor in the yard. Summit Contracting, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and discovered four tank cars (ITDX 5049, ITDX 135196, TILX 13580 and NDYX 113547) loaded with Molten Sulfur to be leaking vapors from the tops of the cars. The shipper, International Commodities Export Corp, was notified via CHEMTREC, Report # 2009-11-24-00065. Summit representatives found one of the 4 tank cars, ITDX 5049, to have a deteriorated manway cover gasket.  Summit personnel replaced the deteriorated manway cover gasket and secured the manway cover. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to Ms. Joanne Welker, International Commodities Export Corp, phone number 832-764-5003.  The vapor leak was secured and the car was released for transport. This incident did not require a special switching move.  Cause Code: 209  NARRI:  5 (5+1+0) x (2+0) = 60

column168: Florida Rock & Tank Lines, Inc. driver was delivering ultra low sulfur diesel to a customer location, while getting ready to unload the driver realized the tank charts at the gas station had been updated but he did not have the new charts. The driver took a stick reading at the tank and showed just under 60 inches, the veeder root reading showed 58.78 inches. The driver should have been able to fit 1584 gallons. While unloading the driver felt the hose jump at which time the hose disconnected, leaking approximately 10-15 gallons onto the concrete, driver immediately shut off the flow of product. Most of the spill was contained but it was estimated that 1/2 of a gallon may have reached the drainage area. The spill was cleaned up with 120 lbs of absorbant and SWS First Response was called to the scene. SWS inspected and ensured the clean up was done satisfactorily. The spill occured after 1122 gallons had been dropped. There should have been no problem fitting more gas into the tank but due to the hose not being properly tightened the pressure of the gas not fitting and the loose closure caused the leak to occur.
column169: The driver was counseled on the unloading procedure and not only is a visual inspection of hose/fittings/couplings required but a driver must double check the setting is secure by tugging on the drop tube.

column168: UTLX 66478 was noted by carrier personnel with product dripping from the bottom outlet valve.  Car isolated and shipper notified.    Shipper representatives, Pettit Environmental, responded and found the bottom outlet valve defective, unable to repair.  The residue of material remaining in the car was drained and captured stopping the release.  The car was cleaned and purged of all material and the outlet plug tightened to stop the release.    Investigation developed that the car was noted with the defective bottom outlet after it was unloaded and prior to releasing into transportation.  The shipper rinsed and drained the car prior to releasing but some rinsate remained in the car.  The contaminated rinsate is what was leaking from the car.    FRA Movement Approval FRA-09110574 was obtained by the shipper prior to releasing the car after this incident.

A Clean Harbor's employee was at a customer site loading material onto a cargo tank motor vehicle.  During the loading process, the driver maintained line fo site with the vehicles load level indicator.  as he neared the maximum capacity on the tank he suspended the loading operation to insure he did not overfill the tank.  Once the transfer operation was complete, the driver began to break down the transfer lines and clearing any residual material into the tank.  During this operation, he noticed that material began to leak from the vent device associated with the pump unit.  The driver immediately secured both the external and internal valves to minimize the relesae.  The driver, along with the shipper's represnetative proceeded to absorb the free lquid that escaped from the vent.  This material was placed into a suitable container and was placed into storage pending off site disposal.
column169: In order to prevent a recurrence, the driver will be retrained in the operating procedures for the tank in question..  AN emphasis will be plced on propoer inspection of the tank before, during and at the conclusion of the loading operation to insure the tank is filled to a point in which sufficient space is left for expansion.  IN addition, a visual check must be done to confirm that the liquid level gauge is accurate as it was evident that the driver loaded more material than the level gauge indicated.  This retraining will include both classroom and in filed instruction.

Driver was taking a sample from the bottom discharge valve on the cargo tank before offloading the product.  He said the external valve was closed but when he opened up the internal valve, product leaked out of the external valve.  He immediately closed the internal valve.  Spill pads were used to wipe up the spill.  The delivery was still able to be completed with no further spillage.
column169: After delivery and wash, the cargo tank was brought into the shop to have the external valve checked.  They couldn't find any problems with it.  It appears that this may have been human error and the driver thought the external valve was closed when in fact in may have been partially open.

column168: Driver was using a product transfer pump to transfer product from the cargo tank to the customer storage tank.  About 1/2 hour into the unload, a section of hose from the pump going to the storage tank, developed a small leak.  Driver immediately shut down and put kitty litter on the spilled material.  Driver had another section of hose to use and completed the delivery without further incident.
column169: We continue with our periodic hose testing to prevent incidents such as this.  The driver did say that he visually inspected the hose before connecting it and he did not see anything of concern.

column168: Driver had completed transferring product from the cargo tank to the customer storage tank using air pressure.  He was trying to clear the product in the 80 feet of transfer hose between the cargo tank and the storage tank by using the air pressure from the trailer.  He cracked the discharged valve open just a little and was walking the hose when a rep came out and told him to close the valve.  The air pressure had caused product in the storage tank to bubble out over the top into the containment area.
column169: The driver should have released some of the air pressure in the cargo tank before opening the valve to clear the line and was advised to do so in the future.

column168: US Forestry employees who witnessed the incident said speed was not a factor. For an undetermined reason, the tractor/trailer unit left the road and rolled down the side of a mountain coming to rest in a creek bed. The tractor ended up on top of the trailer which was overturned as well. Approximately 100 gallons of product leaked out of an opening created when a pressure gauge was broken away from its setting in an air inlet adaptor. As the product leaked it began to solidify (freezing point 275 degrees F). The product leaked slowly for approximately 12 hours. Boom and dikes were set in place for containment of the product.

column168: Pre-loaded trailer was parked on terminal yard. Driver assigned to pick-up and deliver the load arrived at the yard and began his pre-trip walk-around. Once he reached the rear of the trailer he discovered product flowing from the external discharge valve onto the ground. The dust cap was laying on the ground next to the camlock ear ring which was now deformed as though it were pried off the camlock ear. The driver noticed that both the internal and external valves were open allowing the product to flow out of the trailer onto the ground. As the driver began working to close both valves, the terminal manager arrived and assisted. Between 1,600 and 1,700 gallons of product were released. Terminal personnel contained the spill with earthen dikes and an emergency response company was called to clean up the spill. There was no evidence that that any components on the trailer failed. The removal of the dust cap and the opening of the internal and external valves was done intentionally by a vandal or vandals as was reported to Longview police.
column169: The terminal is in the process of installing tamper proof equipment on trailers that are subject to being pre-loaded and parked on the yard.

column168: THE STRAIGHT TRUCK CONTAINING FOUR IBCS HAD JUST COMPLETED FUELING AT WILCO HESS TRUCK STOP.  THE TRUCK PULLED AWAY FROM THE PUMP AND TOOK A LEFT TURN TOWARD THE TRUCK STOP EXIT WHEN THE DRIVER NOTICED THAT THE TANK LOADED ON THE RIGHT REAR SIDE OF THE TRUCK WAS LEAKING.  HE STOPPED THE TRUCK, PHONED 911 FOR ASSISTANCE, AND ATTEMPTED TO SLOW THE LEAK AT THE CURB OR THE PARKING LOT WITH ABSORBENT PADS.  THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE HAD BROKEN OFF AND ALL CONTENTS OF THE IBC LEAKED FROM THE TANK, RUN ACCROSS THE PARKING LOT AND ON TO THE BACK  SIDE OF THE PROPERTY THROUGH A DRAINAGE DITCH THAT RUNS TO AN OPEN FIELD AND THEN TO A DITCH.      GRAHAM FIRE DEPARTMENT AND A & D ENVIRONMENTAL RESPONDED TO THE SCENE.  THE AREA WAS SECURED AND A LOCAL TRUCK WASH BUSINESS WAS EVACUATED AS A PRECAUTION.  THE AREA WAS ASSESSED AND DIKING WAS PERFORMED BY FIRE DEPT CREWS.  A & D ENVIRONMENTAL PERFORMED CLEANUP OPERATIONS AND CONTAINED ALL DIRT WHERE CHEMICAL RAN TO.  NO CHEMICAL WAS LOCATED IN ANY WATER SOURCE.

During the loading process, the fire block valve began to leak. As the driver attempted to tighten a packing nut on the valve stem, the stem separated from the valve body allowing the contents of what had been loaded in to the trailer to release to the atmosphere. We estimate approximately 2,000 gallons of oxygen were vaporized to the atmosphere.
column169: CTI has initiated a more thorough inspection of this particular valve during the 30 day, 90 day, and annual inspection of the cryogenic trailers. This valve is a block valve and not a valve that is used during the loading nor the unloading process. The valve is there to be used in case of a catastrophic event such as a fire, so the contents of the trailer can be shut off completely at the tank outlet, so the oxygen doesn't enhance the combustion process. Drivers have also been given remedial training on inspecting this valve during their pre and post trip inspections. Cryogenic trailers are low pressure non-coded tanks and not subject to hydrostatic or pneumatic testing requirements. Other vehicle crossed centerline of 2 way undivided highway striking truck carrying anhydrous ammonia (UN 1005) head on causing the truck to overturn on hwy 12 exactly on the Minnesota / South Dakota border. The crash caused about 30 pounds of anhydrous ammonia to be released into the atmosphere from a safety relief valve on the trailer before the valve reseated itself, causing the leak to stop. About 75 people from the Eastern edge of Big Stone City, SD. were evacuated as a precaution due to the uncertainity of the integrity of the valve. The anhydrous ammonia was trasnferred from the overturned trailer into a different trailer before uprighting the overturned unit. No additional anhydrous ammonia was released. Highway 12 was closed from 8pm on 11/18 until 5am on 11/19. The evacuation timeframe was the same.
column169: This was an accident where alcohol was involved by the other party that struck the truck. It was completely unexpected and unpredicted.

column168: Driver was traveling westbound on US Route 460 with a tractor trailer combination. The driver veered off the right hand edge of the road. The road shoulder sloped away from the roadway and the driver was unable to steer the unit back onto the highway. Due to the degree of slope, the tractor/trailer rolled over and came to rest on the right hand side of the road shoulder and was completely off the traveled portion of the roadway. The Scott County KY Emergency Response department was called and they responded to the accident scene. This was a single vehicle accident and the driver was unhurt. The cargo was trickling from the tank trailer for about 6 hours. The Emergency Response crew put a dike around the area affected by the leak. Immediate action was taken to locate a replacement tank trailer. During the transfer an estimated 800 gallons was spilled on the ground as the cargo was transferred to another tank trailer. The KY EPA had an area of soil removed from the accident site for disposal and the accident site was restored.

column168: A BNSF switch crew member reported a product odor emanating from CHVX 100113 (DOT 112J340W tank car). CHVX 100113 was cordoned off and activities in the railyard were suspended. A BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder inspected CHVX 100113 finding the B-end liquid valve had frost formed around its closure plug. The responder reported that the wheel valve appeared closed but was able to turn it slightly to its fully closed position and the audible escaping vapor hiss ceased. The B-end liquid valve's closure plug was tight and again the responder was able to turn it to a tool tight condition. Afterwards, BNSF contract responders arrived and proceeded to recheck all valves and fittings. The B-end liquid valve's closure plug was removed, cleaned, Teflon taped, reapplied and tool tightened. Response was concluded by 0340 hrs. CST, 11/12/09. Yard operations resumed after an approximate 2 1/2 hour cessation.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: While unloading anhydrous ammonia at a customer a leak developed in the hose used to connect the trailer to the customers system.  As soon as the leak developed the customers system and the trailer was shut down immediately about 5 seconds).  When the product vacated the hose it was removed and a new one was installed.  There were no evacuations, property damage, environmental impact, or any personal injury or death because of this incident.  About 25 pounds of liquid ammonia was released.

column168: A BNSF switch crew reported SAUX 758 (DOT 112J400W tank car) emanating a product odor in the railyard. SAUX 758 was cordoned off awaiting inspection from BNSF contract responders. The contract responders reported finding the flange bolt nuts on the 300 psi pressure relief device (PRD) not tool tight with product vapor escaping from the PRD flange connection atop the pressure plate. All four PRD flange bolt nuts were tool tightened which ended the product release by 0845 hrs. CST, 11/18/09. All other valves and fittings were found secure.  The side specification stencil on SAUX 758 indicated that the last tank qualification was completed in the year 2002 and the PRD was last qualified by BWS in 2009.

column168: A CALL WAS PLACED TO THE DMP CAGE AT 6:39PM ON 11/25/2009 FROM RON.  RON STATED THERE WAS A LEAKING PACKAGE AT BAY 25.  JERMAINE STOAKLEY RESPONDED TO LEAKING PACKAGE AND PT SUPERVISOR JUANA DIRECTED HIM TO WHERE EXACTLY THE LEAKING PACKAGE WAS LOCATED.  JERMAINE STOAKLEY FOLLOWED THE DECISION TREE AND RESPONSE SHEET AND APPROPRIATELY HANDLED THE LEAKING PACKAGE.  JERMAINE STOAKLEY DETERMINED THAT THE CAP WAS LOOSE WHICH CAUSED CONTENTS TO SPILL ONTO TOP OF THE CONTAINER.  JERMAINE STOAKLEY, REALIZING THAT THE CONTENTS OF WHICH THE LIQUID WERE HELD IN A 5-GALLON CONTAINER AND  OBSERVED ONLY 1 GALLON PRESENT IN THE CONTAINER ASKED PT SUPERVISOR JUANA WAS THERE ANY OTHER PLACE THE LIQUID COULD HAVE SPILLED OUT AND SHE STATED NO.  AFTER READING HAZMAT SHIPPING LABEL, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE PROPER AMOUNT OF LIQUID WAS PRESENT IN THE 5-GALLON CONTAINER WHICH WAS 1 GALLON.  LEAKING PACKAGE WAS THEN BROUGHT TO DMP CAGE TO GO THROUGH DMP PROCESS.
RECEIVED CALL ABOUT A LEAKER ON THE YELLOW BELT AND RESPONDED WITH ALL MY PPE ON.  FOLLOWED MY DECISION TREE AND CONTAINED THE SPILL.  TOOK BACK TO OVERGOODS TO PROCESS THROUGH THE DMP.

column168: THE POLICE REPORT AND THE DRIVER'S REPORT ARE NOT AVAILABLE AT THE CURRENT TIME.  BASED ON OUR EVALUATION OF THE SCENE IT APPEARS THAT THE DRIVER LEFT THE ROADWAY GRADUALLY.  WHEN     THE LOADED TRAILER GOT OFF THE PAYMENT ON THE SOFT, WET SHOULDER, THE DRIVER WAS UNABLE TO GET THE TRAILER BACK ON THE ROADWAY AND IT CONTINUED TO SKID DOWN THE STEEP SHORT EMBANKMENT AND ROLLED OVER.  THE TANK DID NOT RUPTURE AT ANY POINT, BUT THE TWO-LANE ROAD WAS SHUT DOWN FOR A LONG PERIOD OF TIME WHILE EMERGENCY AND HAZMAT CREWS PUMPED OUT THE TANK AND CLEANED UP THE ACCIDENT WRECKAGE.  THE DRIVER SUSTAINED MULTIPLE INJURIES.
column169: Where the driver had just taken a 90-degree right turn about 1 mile before, there is no reason to believe he fell asleep.  Due to the nature that he left the roadway gradually without skid marks, we don't believe he swerved to miss an animal or another vehicle.  The driver is currently in ICU at the hospital and will be interviewed at a more appropriate time.  Until more information is collected, we cannot make a determination as to the root cause of the accident and what precautionary steps or additional training we may suggest to prevent this in the future.

column169: USE DUNNAGE, DECK BARS AND AIR RAGS TO PROPERLY BLOCK AND BRACE FOR SAFELY TRANSPORTATION OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS. PAILS CONTAINING LIQUIDS, HAZARDOUS MATERIALS AND CHEMICALS MUST BE SAFELY CHECKED TO INSURE NOTHING IS ALLOWED TO LEAK OUT. THE PACKAGINGS MUST BE COMPLETELY SHROUDED, BLOCKED AND BRACED BY USING DUNNAGE, PLYWOOD AND OR MW PALLETS. WHEN HANDLING AND MOVING PAILS AND DRUMS, KNOW THE SURROUNDINGS TO ENSURE PRODUCT IS NOT EASILY DAMAGED. RETRAINING IN WORK METHODS ON PROPER AND SAFE LOADING AND HANDLING OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS, LIQUIDS AND CHEMICALS. RECURRENT TRAINING IN HAZARDOUS MATERIALS. WHEN LOADING NOTE THAT BAGS, PAILS OR DRUMS OF LIQUIDS AHEAD. HEAVY FREIGHT LOADED ON THE BOTTOM. LIGHT FREIGHT ON TOP! USE PLENTY OF CUSHIONING BETWEEN LAYERS OF FREIGHT. DO NOT LOAD HEAVY FREIGHT ON TOP OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS. FREIGHT MUST BE SECURELY BLOCKED AND BRACED BEFORE ALLOWING TO MOVE IN TRANSIT!

column42: PETROLEUM GASES, LIQUEFIED OR LIQUEFIED PETROLEUM GAS
column168: ON 11/24/09, AT ABOUT 10:30 AM, DRIVER HAD LOADED AT TARGA RESOURCES IN GILLIS, LA AND WAS ON WAY TO UNLOAD AT CONOCO, WESTLAKE, LA. AT ABOUT 10:30 AM DRIVER CALLED INTO DISPATCH, WHICH IN TURN CALLED SAFETY, TO INFORM US THAT HE HAD ROLLED OVER AT EXIT 29, OFF OF INTERSTATE 10. HE STATED THAT HE WAS LOADED WITH APPROXIMATELY 8300 GALLONS OF ISO BUTANE AND THE TANKER WAS LEAKING. HE STATED THAT HE HAD COME OFF OF THE LAKE CHARLES BRIDGE AND EXITED. HE STATED THAT HE APPLIED THE BRAKES AND THE NEXT THING HE KNEW, HE HAD ROLLED OVER. LOUISIANA HAZMAT WAS NOTIFIED AT ABOUT 10:40 AM AND INCIDENT NUMBER 09-06421 WAS ASSIGNED. THE FEDERAL HOTLINE WAS NOTIFIED AT ABOUT 10:50 AM AND INCIDENT NUMBER 924449 WAS ASSIGNED. STATE TROOPER JOHN DAIRIES WAS ASSIGNED TO INCIDENT. SEAN RICHARDSON AND BRIAN LINZTEN WAS ASSIGNED TO SITUATION TO REPRESENT COMPANY ON MECHANICAL ISSUES. FIRE, EMS AND A REMEDIATION TEAM WERE CALLED IN AFTER THE SITUATION WAS ASSESSED. A POST ACCIDENT DRUG AND ALCOHOL SCREEN WAS DONE WITH IN TWO HOURS OF THE ACCIDENT. DUE TO THE ROLLOVER THE TANKER WAS PUNCTURED ON THE DRIVERS SIDE, FRONT, NEXT TO THE WELD SEAM, WHERE THE FRONT CONE IS ATTACHED. THE METAL WAS PUSHED IN ABOUT 6 INCHES DEEP AND ABOUT 12 INCHES LONG. THIS BREACH WAS CAUSED BY THE TRAILER HITTING THE CURB OF THE ROAD. THE TRAILER LEAK VAPOR FOR ABOUT 4 TO 5 HOURS. A MAGNETIC PATCH WAS PUT OVER THE PUNCTURE AND A MEDIATION TEAM THEN ATTACHED A FLARE TO TRAILER AND FLARED THE REMAINING 2500 GALLONS. THERE WERE OTHER DENTS, BUT THERE WERE NO OTHER PUNCTURES OR LEAKS. THE TANKER WAS THEN UPRIGHTED AND TOWED TO YARD FOR SECUREMENT.
column169: TRAINING ON ROLL OVER PREVENTION WILL BE GIVEN ON A YEARLY BASIS, TO INCLUDE TRAINING ON DEFENSIVE DRIVING.

column168: HLXU was noted leaking less than 2 gallons of unknown product through the flooring of the container.  Interior inspection discovered the lading was floor-loaded 55-gallon drums with palletized pails and cartons stacked on the second tier with no bi-level separation.  The container flooring was covered with plastic sheeting that had absorbent pads covering the plastic sheeting.   Blocking and bracing consisted of improperly applied Ty-Guard that was less than adequate to properly restrain the lading.  Located two open top 55-gallon drums of paint that were leaking at the bungs due to improper securement. A total of four gallons was released.   Also located one closed head drum that was leaking resin at the top rolling hoop from a silicon patch previously applied to the damaged area.  The top rolling hoop was abraded by an adjacent drum rolling hoop.  Approximately 15 gallons of product was released.  This drum should have been placed in a salvage drum for shipment.  The leaking drum was patched and placed into salvage drum for securement.  Several other drums sustained sufficient damage, but did not leak, that required they be placed into salvage drums to continue in transit.  The container was cleaned and the lading, along with the recovery drums, were placed into the original container.  The container was then released for movement onto the local consignee.
column169: Utilize proper loading and securement protocols for transporting hazardous commodities

column168: Container GATU 828922 was reported leaking at East Yard, City of Commerce, CA.  Lading consisted of floor loaded 55-gallon drums, with palletized cartons placed on top of the drums with no bi-level separation.  The only lading securement were two nylon straps attached in a criss-cross fashion to the 'D' rings.  The lading was removed to locate the leaking commodity, which turned out to be a non regulated silicone defoamer for water treatment systems.  The bottom chime of the drum had been damaged during loading from contact with an elevated floor screw.  Approximately 10 gallons of product had been lost.  During the unloading process, located one 30-gallon metal drum marked and labeled as a Flammable Solid, Aluminum Paste, which did not show on the existing billing.  APL was contacted and confirmed this product did not show on their paperwork.  The container was cleaned of the liquid residue.  Due to the condition of the flooring of the existing container, a replacement container, HLXU 454687, was brought in for reloading.  All of the freight was loaded into the replacement container, and once the billing was corrected, released for movement onto the consignee.

column168: MOLO EMPLOYEE DRIVING A SEMI TRUCK AND TRAILER CROSSED THE I-74 BRIDGE TRAVELING EAST AND TOOK THE 7TH AVE EXIT #2.  HE TURNED LEFT ON 7TH AVE TRAVELING EAST AND FOLLOWED THE ROAD TURNING LEFT ON 23RD STREET STARTING THE FIRST TURN IN A S-TURN.  TRAVELING TO THE INTERSECTION OF 23RD ST AND 6TH AVE HE HAD A GREEN LIGHT FOR A RIGHT TURN.  THE DRIVER LOOKED BOTH WAYS AND DID NOT SEE ANY VEHILCES IN THE INTERSECTION.  WITH THE INTERSECTION CLEAR THE DRIVER CONTINUED THROUGH THE RIGHT TURN AND FELT THE TRUCK TIP ON ITS LEFT SIDE.  THE DRIVER PUT THE TRUCK IN NEUTRAL AND TRIED TO GAIN CONTROL OF THE VEHICLE AND THEN THE TRUCK TIPPED OVER ONTO IT'S LEFT SIDE AS THE VEHICLE REACHED THE END OF THE TURN.  THE BULKHEADS BETWEEN COMPARTMENTS 1 AND 2, 3 AND 4 RUPTURED.  GAS LEAKED FROM DRAIN HOLES LOCATED BETWEEN EACH COMPARTMENT.  THE LEAKS LASTED FOR APPROXIMATELY 10 MINUTES.  THE HAZMAT TEAM STOPPED THE LEAKS USING STOP LEAK PUTTY.
column169: SLOW DOWN BEFORE CURVES AND ACCELERATE THROUGH THE CURVE.  MAKE SURE THE LOAD IS EVENLY DISTRIBUTED ON THE TRUCK.  AVOID RUSHING AND DRIVE SAFELY.

column168: ENGINE BNSF 2085 WAS SITTING ON FUELING TRACK, BUT OFF OF THE THE FUELING DRIP PAN.  CONTRACTOR WAS IN THE PROCESS OF FUELING THE BNSF 2085 AND WENT TO HIS TRUCK FOR SOMETHING AND THE FUEL NOZZLE CAME OUT AND FELL ON THE GROUND SPILLING DIESEL ON THE GROUND.  ABOUT 15 TO 20 GALLONS SPILLED ON THE GROUND BEFORE THE CONTRACTOR SHUT THE NOZZLE OFF.  BELFOR ENVIRONMENTAL WAS CALLED TO DO THE CLEAN UP.
column169: CONTRACTOR WAS TOLD TO ONLY FUEL ENGINES WHEN THEY WERE OVER THE FUELING DRIP PANS.  STAY WITH NOZZLE AT ALL TIMES WHEN WHEN FUELING.

column168: DRIVER WAS UNLOADING DIESEL INTO TANK AT PIC # 5 IN CENTER MISSOURI.  THE CONES WERE IN PLACE WARNING DRIVERS OF HOSE.  AS DRIVER CAME AROUND TRUCK A VEHICLE WAS BACKING OVER THE DROP ELBOW THAT HOOKS INTO THE UNDERGROUND TANK.  OUR DRIVER SHUT OFF THE FUEL FLOW AND THEN PICKED UP THE HOSE SO AS NO MORE FUEL WAS ON GROUND.  THE VEHICLE THAT BROKE THE ELBOW ALSO BACK OVER THE CONE, WHICH IS USED AS A WARNING TO DRIVERS TO BE CAUTIOUS. column168: THE UNLOADER WAS UNLOADING THE NOSE TRAILER (APPROX. 75% DONE) IN THE PRIMARY WHEN HE FOUND THAT A BOX HAD SPILLED SOME MATERIAL ON HIM BUT DID NOT KNOW WHICH BOX IT WAS. HE DISCOVERED THE BOX AT 07:20 AM ON THE PRIMARY BELT BECAUSE THE SPLITTERS SAW IT AS IT CONTINUED PAST THEM. THE BOX WAS PICKED OFF AND PUT IN SPILL TRAY AS QUICKLY AS POSSIBLE. THERE WERE APPROXIMATLY 20 OTHER PACKAGES THAT HAD COME INTO CONTACT WITH THE MATERIAL. THE UNLOADER NOTICED A SHORT TIME LATER THAT ORDER EVERYONE WHO CAME INTO CONTACT WITH THE PKG FELT SIMILAR SYMPTOMS. THE REASON WAS UNKNOWN BECAUSE THE BOX HAD ONLY MARKINGS FOR A COMMON DEGREASER AND ORIENTATION ARROWS. AN INVESTIGATION BY THE DESIGNATED RESPONDER SHOWED THAT THE 20 LBS OF CAUSTIC SODA LYE IS A CORROSIVE MATERIAL PER THE MSDS THROUGH 3E ONLINE. NOBODY HOSPITALIZED, ALL EFFECTED WASHED ENDING IN MINOR BURNS

column168: An MLG tractor trailer left the roadway and scraped the ripped the side of the trailer open and coming to an abrupt stop once striking a rock ledge adjacent to the roadway.  As a result of the trailer being ripped open and sudden stop, the totes within the trailer slammed into the front of the trailer and ruptured.  A total of 15 totes were on the trailer in which 5 totes were regulated by the DOT (1-UN2922, 3-UN3265, 1-UN1719: other reports to follow).      All totes were damaged and released material onto the soils beneath the tractor and ditch leading to a culvert passing underneath the NB lanes, through the median and towards Salmon Stream.  It will remain unknown how much material was released and affected the stream however no adverse affects have been noted after numerous thorough investigations of the area.      ERTS dispatched TMC Environmental Services to the site for initial response and remediation activities.  The bulk of the released material was removed and containerized into poly drums for disposal activities.  The affected soils on the shoulder of the NB lanes were excavated and containerized for transportation and disposal activities.  Site maintenance was conducted for approximately 2 weeks which involved removal of product saturated in the rock ledge and pushed out through rain and groundwaters.  The affected waters were stored in Frac tanks until liquid disposal was possible.    The site will be evaluated once again in the spring per the Maine DEQ's request to ensure that no further activities are required.

column168: BNSF intermodal (IM) hub workers reported a product odor emanating from a 20 foot intermodal container MSKU 212649 that was entrained on a rail flatcar that arrived earlier on a BNSF inbound train. MSKU 212649 was an overseas import shipment that arrived in the U.S. at Los Angeles Harbor. MSKU 212649 was carefully deramped and immediately taken to the IM facility's containment area. BNSF contract responders removed and inspected pallets of drums that were inside MSKU 212649. The last pallet removed from MSKU 212649 revealed one 55 gallon steel drum that had leaked product from a stress fracture/hairline crack on this drum's bottom head. The drum's bottom rim showed no signs of impact dents or damage. The responders placed this damaged drum into an 85 gallon over-pack drum and staged it for appropriate disposal. Spillage inside MSKU 212649 that didn't evaporate was absorbed with absorbent padding. Afterwards, all the remaining lading was returned into MSKU 212649 properly blocked and braced for highway transportation furtherance.

A BNSF switch crew reported a product odor emanating from TILX 110097 (DOT 111A100W5 tank car) in the railyard. TILX 110097 was cordoned off awaiting inspection from BNSF responders. Inspection of TILX 110097 revealed a blown 165 psi frangible disc. A BNSF contractor was called to assist in obtaining and installing a suitable replacement frangible disc; as well as, cleaning product spillage from the side shell of TILX 110097. The replacement 165 psi frangible disc was installed without further incident. Product spillage was neutralized and wiped. Response was concluded by 1150 hrs. PST, 11/23/09.

column168: A BNSF inbound train inspection in the railyard revealed entrained LTCX 1924 (DOT 113A90W tank car) venting from its side operating (equipment) compartment. BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responders were immediately summoned to inspect LTCX 1924. The shipper seals on the operating compartment were found intact. The responders broke the seals and opened the operating compartment doors. The compartment's interior was iced over and the responders noted a stainless steel pipe that had broken off at its threaded connection into a valve, which was later identified as a tri-cock valve used to gauge the liquid levels inside this tank car. LTCX 1924 was setout from the train; carefully moved and isolated in the railyard. LTCX 1924 continued to be monitored and the venting ebbed as it awaited repairs by a shipper technician/responder. On 11/30/09, the shipper responder tapped threads inside the pipe at the break location; inserted and secured a stainless steel bolt into the pipe to plug it. Afterwards, no further release of product was evident.

column168: A BNSF yard switch job in the railyard pulling railcars out of a classification track across a power operated switch derailed five railcars at the switch. The cause of this derailment was attributed to a switch malfunction and improper use of this power switch. One of the railcars derailed was TILX 314693 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) that derailed leaning with its trucks out from under this tank car. TILX 314693's bottom outlet valve (BOV) was sheared off up to the flange connection from impact with the ground, exposing the internal ball in this valve. A slight product drip emanated from around the BOV's internal ball seal. BNSF responders and contract responders placed containment under the BOV to catch the drips. TILX 314693 was rerailed and staged for product transfer with containment in place under the damaged BOV. Product within TILX 314693 was transferred into another suitable tank car on 12/02/09 without further incident. Product that was captured in the containment receptacle evaporated. TILX 314693 was cleaned and purged of hazardous material after the product transfer was completed.

column168: A VEHICLE MOUNTED CARGO INSPECTION SYSTEM THAT USES A RADIOACTIVE SOURCE (CESIUM 137) TO PRODUCE GAMMA RAYS FOR IMAGING WAS BEING SHIPPED FROM FORT DRUM, NEW YORK, USA TO BAGRAM AIRFIELD, AFGHANISTAN.  THE SYSTEM IS THE MOBILE VEHICLE AND CARGO INSPECTION SYSTEM (MVACIS), MANUFACTURED BY SAIC, INC.  THE MILITARY UNIT OFFERING THE MVACIS FOR SHIPMENT IDENTIFIED IT AS A MOTOR VEHICLE MOUNTED X-RAY SYSTEM.  IT FAILED TO IDENTIFY THAT IT CONTAINED RADIOACTIVE MATERIAL.  THE FT DRUM TRANSPORTATION OFFICE (TO) PREPARED THE SHIPPING DOCUMENTATION.  SINCE THE MVACIS IS A COMMERICAL ITEM, IT IS NOT LISTED EITHER IN THE FEDERAL LOGISTICS (FEDLOG) OR HAZARDOUS MATERIAL IDENTIFICATION SYSTEM (HMIS), THE TO COULD NOT IDENTIFY THE RADIOACTIVE MATERIAL STATUS.  THE TO FURTHER CHECKED THE SAIC WEBSITE FOR THE MVACIS.  THEREIN, IT WAS IDENTIFIED AS A "GAMMA-RAY IMAGING" SYSTEM.  THIS DID NOT INDICATE ANY HAZMAT STATUS TO THE TO.  SHIPMENT OF THE MVACIS WAS STARTED 17 NOV 2009 AS CLASS ITEM # 190190 VEHICLES, MOTOR.  THE IMPROPER SHIPMENT WAS IDENTIFIED BY THE INSTALLATION RADIATION SAFETY OFFICER 20 NOV 2009.
column169: THE MVACIS WAS A ONE-OF-KIND ITEM ON THE INSTALLATION.  ACQUIRING ANOTHER SIMILAR COMMERCIAL SYSTEM IS NOT ANTICIPATED.  ALL OTHER HAZMAT ITEMS ARE LISTED IN FEDLOG AND OR HMIS.  THERE SHOULD BE NO OPPORTUNITY FOR RECURRENCE.  - A SUGGESTION HAS BEEN SENT TO SAIC INC. THAT THEY USE THE WORD "RADIOACTIVE" ON THE WEB PAGE TO INDICATE THE HAZMAT STATUS TO UNTRAINED PERSONS.  - AT THE CONCLUSION OF THE FORMAL INVESTIGATION REGARDING THIS INCIDENT, A SUGGESTION WILL BE SENT UP THE CHAIN OF COMMAND THAT ARMY, CENTRALLY PROCURED, COMMERCIAL ITEMS BE LISTED FOR THEIR HAZMAT STATUS IN FEDLOG AND HMIS.

column168: UTCU 450236 (INTERMODAL TANK CONTAINER, AAR U621) DESTINED FOR OVERSEAS EXPORT ARRIVED ON A BNSF TRAIN WITH INTERMODAL FLATCARS AND STAGED FOR UNLOADING.  DURING THE DERAMPING (LIFTING THE INTERMODAL CONTAINER FROM THE RAIL FLATCAR ONTO A CHASSIS FOR GROUND MOVEMENT) OF UTCU 450236 FROM ITS INTERMODAL FLATCAR, THE BOTTOM LIQUID VALVE EXTENSION THAT PROTRUDED BEYOND THIS TANK CONTAINER'S OUTER SUPPORT FRAME STRUCTURE INADVERTENTLY CONTACTED THE RAILCAR FRAMEWORK.  THIS CONTACT RESULTED IN A TANK COMPROMISE AND PRODUCT RELEASE WHEN THE BOTTOM OUTLET FLANGE PLATE BROKE AWAY FROM THE TANK CONTAINER SHELL.  BNSF RESPONSE CONTRACTORS ESTABLISHED AIR MONITORING.  THE LOCAL FD AND COUNTY HAZARDOUS MATERIAL RESPONSE UNITS APPLIED FIRE SUPPRESSANT FOAM ON AND AROUND THE SPILL AREA OF FIRE, ODOR AND LIQUID FLOW ABATEMENT.  THE PRODUCT WITHIN UTCU 450236 WAS TRANSFERRED TO TANK TRUCK TO BE RETURNED TO THE PRODUCT MANUFACTURER AND WAS COMPLETED WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT BY APPROXIMATELY 1340 HRS. PST, 11/06/09.  THE PAVED GROUND SPILLAGE WAS VACUUMED AND WATER WASHED AFTERWARDS.  NEARBY STORM DRAINS WERE INSPECTED AND CLEANED.  THE RECOVERED PRODUCT SPILLAGE WITH CAPTURED FOAM AND WATER WAS TRANSPORTED OFF PROPERTY FOR PROPER DISPOSAL.  TWO LA COUNTY FD RESPONDERS WERE TAKEN TO A LOCAL HOSPITAL.  BOTH EXAMINED AND RELEASED; ONE FOR INHALATION EXPOSURE AND THE OTHER FOR SKIN EXPOSURE FROM THE RELEASING PRODUCT.  ONE BNSF EMPLOYEE THAT WAS OPERATING A VEHICLE NEAR THE INITIAL PRODUCT RELEASE AREA WAS EXAMINED FOR INHALATION EXPOSURE AND RELEASED WITHOUT FURTHER TREATMENT.

column168: On Monday, November 9 2009, at 2130 hours CST, Sue LeBlanc, from Quality Carriers Sky Tank contacted American Compliance Technologies, Inc. (A•C•T) Project Manager, Mr. Wayne Koszegi, CHMM to request assistance with a toluene spill and product transfer. The spill occurred at the Lee Hi Travel Plaza located at 2516 North Lee Road (I-81, Exit 195) in Lexington, Virginia.  Ms. LeBlanc advised that a weld cracked on tanker #8654 and less than 5-gallon of toluene was released onto the asphalt parking lot and that the load would have to be transferred to another tanker. Mr. Koszegi contacted Mr. Keith Thorton, the Quality Carriers driver to determine if any stormwater drains or soil were impacted.  Mr. Thorton reported that no drains or soil were impacted.  The VA-DEQ was notified of this incident and report #HMVA 5988 was issued.        Upon arrival at the site, our response team advised that the Lexington Fire Department had closed the truck stop and placed fire hose across a highway closing it in both directions.  The fire chief would not let our responders enter the “hot zone” until the fire chief determined it was safe.  Multiple fire hose lines were placed in the area by the fire dept as a precaution.  Ms. LeBlanc advised that a clean tanker was en route to the site.  The regional hazardous material response team (haz-mat) was mobilized to the site at the direction of the local fire chief.  Upon arrival, the haz-mat team investigated the area and established air monitoring stations.      Once the fire chief allowed our response team to make entry to the tanker, absorbent pads and boom was applied to a small area of contamination on the asphalt.      The clean tanker arrived on site at 0500 hours local time and product transfer operations began.  The product transfer was concluded at approximately 0745 hours local time.  All contaminated pads and boom were collected and containerized into a 55-gallon drum for disposal.      All fire department hose lines were removed from the highway at approximately 0800 hours local time and the truck stop was re-opened.    WASTE DISPOSAL    As a result of the response activities, one (1) drum of contaminated pads and boom was generated. Upon profile approval, the waste was manifested and transported to Ecoflo in Greensboro, North Carolina for disposal.

column168: On Tuesday, November 3, 2009, at 1216 hours EST, Ms. Terry Budd, from Quality Distribution’s Sky Tank contacted American Compliance Technologies, Inc. (A•C•T) Project Manager, Mr. Wayne Koszegi, CHMM to request assistance with a spill of Furfuryl Alcohol Urea Formaldehyde Polymer Resin.  The spill occurred on the United States side of the Peace Bride in Buffalo, New York. Ms. Budd advised that the product was leaking from the washout cap and was mostly contained on the tanker sides and a small area on the pavement. Mr. Koszegi contacted Officer Deacon from the U.S. Customs Service who confirmed the initial reports.  No soil or waterways were impacted.  Officer Deacon also advised that the NY-DEC was notified of this incident.    Upon arrival at the site, our response team advised that the impacted area was contained on the asphalt roadway and a small section of the tanker.  No soil or waterways were impacted shown in the Maps and Photographs section of this report.     Our response team began the cleanup process by applying granular sorbents to the spilled material located on the paved surfaces surrounding the trailer.  The tanker side was scraped to remove the resin.  All waste was containerized into one (1) 55-gallons drum for disposal.  Officer Deacon approved the cleanup operations and released the truck to continue on its route.     WASTE DISPOSAL    As a result of the response activities, one (1) drum of resin-contaminated sorbent was generated.  Upon profile approval, the waste was manifested and transported to CVM-Waste Management Facility in Model City, New York, a Quality Distribution approved disposal facility.

On Thursday, November 12, 2009, at 1415 hours EST, Ms. Kathy Cronin, from Quality Carriers contacted American Compliance Technologies, Inc. (A•C•T) Nationwide Project Manager, Mr. Gary L. Weiss to request assistance with the transload of a corrosive chemical. The incident location is at a Quality Carriers Facility at 1251 Battle Creek Road in Jonesboro, Georgia.  Ms. Cronin advised that tanker #69320 developed a valve problem that required the chemical to be transloaded into another tanker.  Additionally, a nitrogen blanked would have to be applied to the new tanker during the transload process.  Quality Carriers advised that they would supply the clean tanker and nitrogen gas for site activities.      The product that needed to be transloaded was Vestamin IPD (Isophoron Diamine) a colorless corrosive liquid with a UN 1040 marking.   A•C•T reviewed the MSDS and all safety precautions with our response team prior to any site operations.    Upon arrival at the site, our response team met with Mr. Mark Bryan, the Operations Supervisor and inspected the leaking tanker.  The tanker had a capacity of 6,000 gallons of product and Quality Carriers personnel had stopped the leak. Due to the fact that it was a bottom valve that was compromised, as shown in Figure 2 of the Maps and Photographs section of this report, our response team was unable to pressurize the vessel to blow the product over because the valve might sheer off due to any surge.    After consulting with Mr. Rob Smale, from Quality Distribution it was decided to return in the morning and use a the Quality Carrier Tanker pump to transload the product      On Friday, November 13, 2009, our response team returned to the site to complete all operations.  Once the Quality Carriers tanker arrived, it was determined that it was not large enough to hold the entire load.  A different tanker was requested.  Once the second tanker arrived our response team established a closed loop transfer system utilizing hoses provided by Quality carrier to transload the product.  A six (6) PSI blanket of nitrogen was placed in the tanker to complete the transload operation.    WASTE DISPOSAL    As a result of the response activities, one (1) drum of approximately 5 gallons of product, PPE and boom was left onsite per Mr. Smale.  Quality Distribution will dispose of the waste via their waste contractor.

column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  While traveling, vehicle was involved in an accident, which resulted in the release of approximately 1,500 gallons of chlorite solution.  The free product released to the soil adjacent to the roadway.  H2O Environmental of Salt Lake City, Utah was dispatched to perform the cleanup.  Upon arrival on site, H2O Environmental held a safety meeting, confirmed site was stablized, damaged totes had been offloaded from trailer, and vehicle was uprighted and hauled off site.  Site was secured, pending applicable permits and utility locates. H2O Environmental returned the following day to berm the area downgradient from the incident site, to prevent migration, pending disposal approval and applicable permits.  On November 30, 2009, H2O Environmental returned to the site to commence excavation activities.  Approximately 1,500 tons of contaminated soil were recovered from the incident site.  Confirmation samples were taken, and returned within acceptable limits. Site was backfilled and restored to preexisting condition.  Contaminated soil was transported by H2O Environmental to Sweetwater County Landfill in Rock Springs, Wyoming for disposal.  There were no injuries or exposures reported.
column169: Since the release was accidental, and appears to be related to a vehicle accident, no plans currently exist to prevent recurrence.  Benchmark Distribution Services will continue to train and reinforce safe handling procedures and driver safety to all personnel.

column168: Our truck was transporting a load of gasoline from the Magellin terminal in Aurora, CO to Durango, CO.  Our driver was on hwy 160 8 miles east of South Fork, CO at 14:50 local time when as he put it, "the truck started to head towards the right hand shoulder of the road".  Despite all efforts on his part he could not get the truck to respond to any of his recovery actions.  The result was a collision with the rock side of the mountain road that compromised both the front and the back compartments of the trailer.  The conditions were lite snow and and breezy, and the road was wet as a result of the snow.  As a result of this collision with the side of the mountain approxamatly 3800 gallons of gasoline leaked from the two ruptured compartments.  The included narrative from the Colorado State Patrol is the best description of the events that followed.      Our driver (William Shelton) has worked for us since 1991 and has never had an incident of this nature or even a reportable accident that was his fault.  He was going less than the posted speed limit and has driven these same mountain roads for many years.

column168: INCIDENT OCCURRED WHEN AN AUTOMOBILE RAN OVER A HOSE THAT WAS BEING USED TO FILL AN UNDERGROUND STORAGE TANK (UST) AT THE SITE.  THE HOSE NOZZLE DISCONNECTED FROM THE UST WHILE  GASOLINE WAS STILL FLOWING FROM THE DELIVERY TRUCK.  THE DELIVERY TRUCK DRIVER IMMEDIATELY CLOSED THE TRAILER VALVES TO TERMINATE THE FLOW.  IT IS ESTIMATED THAT 20 - 30 GALLONS OF GASOLINE WAS SPILLED.  THE DELIVERY TRUCK DRIVER THEN RESPONDED TO THE SPILL BY USING SPILL PADS FROM THE TRUCK SPILL KIT TO CURTAIL PRODUCT FROM FLOWING TO THE STREET.  SOME PRODUCT MANAGED TO REACH THE STREET WHERE IT ENTERED A STORM SEWER CATCH BASIN.  IT THEN FLOWED THROUGH THE CATCH BASIN TO A SMALL PERENNIAL STREM KNOWN AS CABIN BRANCH LOCATED ADJACENT TO THE NORTHERN PROPERTY BORDER.  THE LOCAL FIRE DEPT. AND HAZMAT UNIT RESPONDED TO THE SPILL.  HAZMAT UNIT RESPONDED BY PLACING SORBENT BOOMS IN CABIN CREEK.  MARSHALL MILLER & ASSOCIATES (MMA) RESPONDED TO THE SPILL AND CONTINUED THE SPILL CLEANUP.  MMA CLEANED THE STORM SEWER CATCH BASIN, USED SORBENT PADS TO CLEAN THE SURFACE OF THE WATER IN THE STREAM, AND REPLACED THE SORBENT BOOMS.  ONCE MMA COMPLETED THEIR WORK, LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT FLUSHED WATER DOWN THE STREET THROUGH THE STORM SEWER.  AFTER THE INITIAL RESPONSE, MMA RETURNED TO THE SITE AND REMOVED THE SORBENT BOOMS FROM THE STREAM.  A TOTAL OF THREE DRUMS OF DEBRIS AND SATURATED SORBENT MATERIAL WAS DISPOSED AT RECO BIOTECHNOLOGY, RICHMOND, VA.  A COPY OF THE MANIFEST IS PROVIDED.  IN ADDITION TO REPORTING THE RELEASE TO THE STATE OF VIRGINIA, IT WAS ALSO REPORTED TO THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER.  GREEN MOTOR LINES SUBMITTED THE REQUIRED SECTION 308(A) RESPONSE TO THE EPA

column168: On November 19, 2009 at approximately 0800 Trooper Schropfer was on duty In the Hebron area. At that time he heard a page from the Thayer county dispatch center to the Bruning rescue squad saying there had just been a crash on Highway 81 at the junction of Highway 4. Immediately after the page Sergeant Linton advised Thayer   County Dispatch that he and Trooper Schropfer would be in route to the scene. Sergeant Linton then called Trooper Schropfer on the radio to ensure he had heard the page and was in route. Trooper Schropfer advised that he had heard and was in route. At the time there was a very thick fog in the area which can be seen by the responding officers in car cameras. The responding officers observed the fog the entire time that they were in route including at the scene of the crash.     Sergeant Linton was the first to arrive on the scene. He advised that it was at the north junction of Highways 4 and 81. He also advised there were two trucks and a car involved. One of the trucks was displaying red placards with an identification number of 1075. 1075 is the United Nations identification number for Propane.     At approximately 0814 Trooper Schropfer arrived on the scene. As he arrived he asked Lincoln Dispatch to have more people in route to help control traffic because he observed that the fog was still very thick. Trooper Schropfer estimated the visibility at the time to be approximately 200 feet. He also observed that one of the trucks involved had been pulling a cargo tank which was marked indicating that it was carrying propane. The other truck involved had stopped with its cab under the propane trailer, and the car involved had had ran into the front   bumper of the first truck (see accident report and diagram indicating final rest of vehicles).     After Trooper Schropfer exited his vehicle it was discovered that there was a small propane leak on the rear of the cargo tank. It appeared to be coming from the packing around one of the hand valves for the rear outlets. Trooper Schropfer was contacted by Joel L Voss who indicated that he had been driving the truck pulling the cargo tank. Voss stated that he had looked at the cargo tank, and that was the only leak he had observed. It was determined that the emergency shut off on the tank was closed so that after the propane leaked out of that pipe it should stop leaking. Trooper Schropfer made the decision that they would let It leak, and just keep the immediate area clear of ignition sources. At this time Trooper Schropfer cut the battery cables for the truck under the propane trailer. The battery cables for the truck pulling the propane trailer were also disconnected. Trooper Schropfer also made the decision to not attempt to extricate the driver of the second truck, which was a Volvo, because of the risk of creating an ignition source around the propane leak. Based on the amount of damage to, and the where the cab was at final rest Trooper Schropfer determined that It was probab

column168: ON NOVEMBER 4, 2009 AT APPROXIMATELY 2:30AM, A DIESEL TRANSPORT TRACTOR-TRAILER CARRYING 7,500 GALLONS OF DIESEL FUEL WAS TRAVELING ON US HIGHWAY 62/180 THROUGH GUADALUPE MOUNTAINS NATIONAL PARK.  A SINGLE VEHICLE ACCIDENT OCCURRED WHICH RESULTED IN A LARGE RELEASE OF DIESEL FUEL THAT WAS BEING TRANSPORTED IN THE TRAILER.  APPROXIMATELY 5,800 GALLONS OF DIESEL FUEL WERE RELEASED.  ECO-LOGICAL ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES WAS THE PRIMARY ENVIRONMENTAL CONSULTANT DURING THE INITIAL RESPONSE AND REMEDIATION PORTIONS OF THE SPILL CLEAN-UP.  AS THE INSURANCE REPRESENTATIVE FOR JUNG OIL, MICHAEL WHITE WITH CATOLINA CASUALTY HAD AUTHORITY OVER DECISIONS REGARDING THE ENVIRONMENTAL REMEDIATION OF THE DIESEL SPILL IN GUADALUPE MOUNTAINS NATIONAL PARK.  THIS REPORT IS PREPARED BY ECO-LOGICAL ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES ON BEHALF OF JUNG OIL COMPANY AND THE CAROLINA CASUALTY INSURANCE COMPANY AND DETAILS ALL ENVIRONMENTAL REMEDIATION ACTIVITES IN RELATION TO THE DIESEL SPILL REFERENCED ON THE TITLE PAGE.  THIS REPORT IS INTENDED TO BE USED AS A STAND-ALONE DOCUMENT WHEN SUBMITTED TO THE TEXAS COMMISSION ON ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY TO DETAIL THE REMOVAL OF DIESEL AFFECTED MATERIALS, AND CAN BE USED AS A STANDALONE DOCUMENT FOR OTHER ENVIRONMENTAL CONCERNS RELATED TO THE DIESEL SPILL AS LONG AS THE FULL, COMPLETE REPORT IS USED.  THIS REPORT WILL ALSO BE USED IN A LARGER VOLUME PREPARED BY SALLY FISHER WITH BERGERABAM, INC., DETAILING ALL ACTIVITIES IN RESPONSE TO THE DIESEL SPILL, INCLUDING ROAD RECONSTRUCTION AND LAND RESTORATION ACTIVITIES.  THE LARGER REPORT IS TO BE SUBMITTED TO THE UNITED STATES NATIONAL PARK SERVICE (NPS), THE TEXAS DEPARTMENT OF TRANSPORTATION (TXDOT), AND THE CAROLINA CASUALTY INSURANCE COMPANY (CAROLINA).  REPORT ATTACHED.

column168: A Con-way Charlotte, NC Driver was on his way to Atlanta, GA when another Con-Way driver informed him that his trailer was secreting a liquid. The NCH DSR pulled into Greenville, SC to address the situation before continuing to Atlanta, GA. Contacted Linehaul, called emergency response number listed, however their was a message when I called stating that the number was unavailable at the present time.
column169: Investigate the cause and address when final determination is completed.

column168: 1900 HEARD PAGE FOR HAZMAT RESPONDER, TO THE AIR DOCK.  UPON ARRIVING, NOTICED WETNESS ON BOX FOR A TRUE HAZMAT, FLAMMABLE  LIQUID, IMMEDIATELY FOLLOWED THE DECISION TREE TO THE APPROPRIATE RESPONSE SHEET FOR FLAMMABLE LIQUID.  DONNED MY GOGGLES, GLOVES, BOOTS, APRON TO SAFELY REMOVE THE PKG TO THE SERVICE CENTER ACCORDING TO THE RESPONSE SHEET.
RESPONDED TO A SHIPMENT IN WING D, POSI 4, CHUTE 29 DUE TO A RETAPE AND DISCOVERED UNDECLARED DRY ICE. NO SIGNS OF ABUSE TO OUTER PACKAGING. PROCESSED TO FAA WITH PHOTOS.

column58: Air Inlet; Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Non-Reclosing
column168: Due to damage sustained in the accident, the trailer dome air actuated valve was torn off the trailer and the rupture disk was breached, allowing the product release. The product on the bridge was neutralized with soda ash. The product that ran off the bridge was contained by the excavation of a dirt containment area, preventing the entry of product into any sewer or waterway. All of the recovered material was disposed of at an approved site.

The pail was unloaded with leakage noted.  Examination of the pail revealed the pail had been punctured and leaked.  The leakage was contained and the package was repacked.  Undamaged product was returned to the shipper.  The damaged product was properly disposed of in accordance with Federal Regulations.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: The package was unloaded with leakage noted on the box.  Examination of the inner container revealed that the container(s) had loose cap(s) and leaked.  The leakage was contained.  The cap(s) were secured.  The carton was wet but otherwise undamaged.  The undamaged portion of the package was repacked for return to shipper.
